<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
<emphasis bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Notes</emphasis>
. The corolla is consistently 3-3.5 cm long, not 2.5 cm, as stated by McDonald (1992) so corolla size is unreliable in separating this species from 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Ipomoea" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="gesneriodes">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Ipomoea gesneriodes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">A night-flowering, possibly bat-pollinated species.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
The specimen at MO (
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">H.C. Cutler</emphasis>
8414) from 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Ceará">Ceara</normalizedToken>
, Brazil, identified as 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Ipomoea" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="bombycina">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Ipomoea bombycina</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by McPherson is leafless and flowerless and is almost certainly not this species. It might, for example, be 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Ipomoea" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="eremnobrocha">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">I. eremnobrocha</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, which has similar seeds and is known from several states in NE Brazil.
</paragraph>
